Author: blackjok3r#3181
Content: Blaster now works with previous TXID as first 64 chars of OP_RETURN and next 8 chars as sequence number. Just need to add a queue to get data in, still uses random at the moment.

Author: blackjok3r#3181
Content: Thinking sequence number could be usless, thauhgt about it but decided to leave it there for now.

Author: blackjok3r#3181
Content: RPC to add data to queue... with first TXID is all 0, rest point to the last txid, so the txids will order the data anyway it seems, as long as the queue never gets mixed up.

Content: good decision to keep the seqid, it allows for error check

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: uthash.h

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: it has hashing and even simple queue stuff

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: i use DL_APPEND to add to a queue and then you can iterate through the queue

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: read all the uthash docs, it will make you a much more efficient coder

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: http://www.cs.bu.edu/~jappavoo/Resources/psml/apps/hashy/uthash/doc/userguide.html

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: https://troydhanson.github.io/uthash/utlist.html

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: utlist is the queue, start with that

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: you can grep my code for the actual usages

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: i cant remember how many places i used it

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: basically when a new item comes in, malloc a structure, set the fields, DL_APPEND

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: now its in the list

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: where you need to query the list, just do that and if it returns something at the head of the list, you get a FIFO

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: if you get something from the tail of the list it is LIFO

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: really you MUST understand fully about how to use lists and hashtables. with utlist/uthash you dont have to learn to write the internals (though that in itself is very good learning when time is available)

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: 80% of computing is searching and sorting, something like that
